he eyes of some, decidedly Jewish; considers bras, breasts, and the storied skills of the bra fitter; asks, from the perspective of a confused and grieving daughter, what it means to cut the body open; and takes a reeling time-trip through myth, culture, and history to look at women’s hair in ancient Rome, Laos, France, Syria, Cuba, India, and her own past. Some pieces investigate the body under emotional or physical duress, while others use the body to consider personal heritage and legacy. Throughout, Shinner writes with elegance and assurance, weaving her wide-ranging thoughts into a firm and fascinating fabric. Turning the category of body books on, well, its ear, You Feel So Mortal offers a probing view of our preoccupation with the body that is both idiosyncratic and universal, leaving us with the deep satisfaction of our shared humanity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aBody image. 0aHuman body -- Folklore. 0aHuman body -- Mythology. 0aHuman bodyvFolklore. 0aHuman bodyxMythology. 0aHuman body. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  abody, essays, essay collection, academic, scholarly, college, university, higher education, anthology, humanity, human nature, biology, female, jewish, identity, self love, collective, historical, social, political, implications, life, living, daily, desire, fear, confusion, feelings, emotions, witty, funny, grief, breasts, daughter, folklore, myth, mythology, hair, rome, laos, france, syria, cuba, international, global, india.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226127804423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226127804/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d